starts directly out of Haiti.

12:17.804 --> 12:20.173
We actually have our own farm,
about 12 hectares,

12:20.173 --> 12:23.176
where we work with the farmers,
they work for us directly,

12:23.176 --> 12:25.778
but then we also work
with cooperatives.
Cooperatives.

12:25.778 --> 12:28.748
Most farmers live on
less than $1 a day.

12:28.748 --> 12:30.183
We are paying double that
to make sure

12:30.183 --> 12:32.785
that anytime they are
coming with castor seeds,

12:32.785 --> 12:34.621
we give
an above‐market price.

12:34.621 --> 12:35.622
Got it. Good.

12:35.622 --> 12:37.690
Okay, so,
what are your sales?

12:37.690 --> 12:39.926
So, we started
the business in 2014.

12:39.926 --> 12:41.961
We did $135,000 in sales.

12:41.961 --> 12:43.129
Okay.
That's not bad.

12:43.129 --> 12:46.633
In 2016, we did $40,000
worth of sales.

12:46.633 --> 12:47.800
Whoa!
What happened?

12:47.800 --> 12:49.135
At the time in 2016,
we were focusing

12:49.135 --> 12:51.838
on actually selling
the castor oil in bulk,

12:51.838 --> 12:55.708
and one of our top clients
actually walked away.

12:55.708 --> 12:56.976
We were still building
the supply chain.

12:56.976 --> 12:59.045
So, you had one client
to represent the majority
of your business?

12:59.045 --> 13:00.647
It was actually
the majority, yes.

13:00.647 --> 13:01.881
So, we decided to pivot.

13:01.881 --> 13:04.751
In 2017, we decided
to go direct‐to‐consumer,

13:04.751 --> 13:07.687
and from there,
our sales jumped to $327,000.

13:07.687 --> 13:08.855
Greiner: Wow.
O'Leary: Okay.

13:08.855 --> 13:10.723
You went into the retail space.
You switched totally.

13:10.723 --> 13:11.858
2018?
What happened last year?

13:11.858 --> 13:13.860
In 2018,
we did $1 million in sales.

13:13.860 --> 13:15.128
And what's
this year look like?
Wow.
Nice.

13:15.128 --> 13:17.930
This year, we project that
we will close at $2 million.

13:17.930 --> 13:19.032
‐Wow.
‐Really?

13:19.032 --> 13:20.833
Why will we have
such a significant jump

13:20.833 --> 13:22.235
in revenue at $2 million?
Mm‐hmm.

13:22.235 --> 13:25.004
So, the reason that we feel that
we're gonna get to $2 million

13:25.004 --> 13:26.272
is that we just secured
a contract

13:26.272 --> 13:29.275
from the largest beauty retailer
in the country, Ulta.

13:29.275 --> 13:32.578
Yeah, and they're
gonna be launching us
in all 1,200 doors.

13:32.578 --> 13:33.313
Do you have a PO on hand?

13:33.313 --> 13:35.248
We have conversations, yeah.
So, we just finished
the contract,

13:35.248 --> 13:38.685
and then we should be getting
the PO in the next few weeks.

13:38.685 --> 13:40.987
How do people know
what this is?

13:40.987 --> 13:42.155
That's a really good
question, Lori.

13:42.155 --> 13:44.223
I would walk by this
and really not know anything.

13:44.223 --> 13:46.225
And that's why we spend
lots of time making sure

13:46.225 --> 13:49.095
that we educate our retail
partners and their staff.

13:49.095 --> 13:50.997
The other thing is
social media.

13:50.997 --> 13:53.866
So, right now,
we have over 100,000 followers

13:53.866 --> 13:55.735
between all
of our social media outlets,

13:55.735 --> 13:57.203
and our customer base ‐‐

13:57.203 --> 13:59.105
they're showing
before‐and‐after pictures,

13:59.105 --> 14:01.808
which we have here that we would
love to show you guys.

14:01.808 --> 14:03.576
This actually
helps grow hair?

14:03.576 --> 14:04.610
Yes.
Yes.

14:04.610 --> 14:06.779
Well!
[ Laughter ]

14:06.779 --> 14:08.014
It helps
to promote hair growth.

14:08.014 --> 14:10.917
That's what we always say.
We say "promote hair growth."

14:10.917 --> 14:13.386
So, male pattern baldness
is a major issue,

14:13.386 --> 14:16.289
and we have one
of our customers ‐‐
again, unsolicited ‐‐

14:16.289 --> 14:18.925
who started using
our Haitian castor oil,

14:18.925 --> 14:20.927
and in three months,
you could see,

14:20.927 --> 14:23.930
at the crown of his head,
that his hair started to grow.

14:23.930 --> 14:26.165
And by the way,
what does this one jar cost?

14:26.165 --> 14:29.769
So, the retail price
is about $22 for our scented

14:29.769 --> 14:32.705
and $16 for
our original castor oil.

14:32.705 --> 14:34.040
And it costs you
what to make it?

14:34.040 --> 14:36.709
It cost me $2.50
to make it.
Corcoran: Wow.

14:36.709 --> 14:38.644
Will you be profitable
this year?

14:38.644 --> 14:39.212
We <i>are</i> profitable.

14:39.212 --> 14:42.148
What did you make in 2018
on the $1 million?

14:42.148 --> 14:44.117
We did about $300,000
on that.

14:44.117 --> 14:45.852
John: And do you
have any debt now?

14:45.852 --> 14:47.086
We do have debt.
How much?

14:47.086 --> 14:48.955
We do have
$300,000 in debt.

14:48.955 --> 14:53.626
You know, what I love
about this business is <i>you.</i>

14:53.626 --> 14:54.193
Thank you.

14:54.193 --> 14:56.863
You could sell
whatever you want to sell.

14:56.863 --> 14:58.831
[ Laughs ]
Extremely persuasive.

14:58.831 --> 15:00.032
But, interestingly,

15:00.032 --> 15:02.201
it's also what I <i>don't</i> like
about the business.

15:02.201 --> 15:04.871
Your business is
too damn dependent

15:04.871 --> 15:06.873
on <i>you</i> selling the product.

15:06.873 --> 15:08.841
That's just not scalable.

15:08.841 --> 15:09.776
I'm out.

15:11.144 --> 15:14.046
Guys, congratulations
with what you've been
able to accomplish.

15:14.046 --> 15:16.716
I just don't see this
being worth $4 million.

15:16.716 --> 15:17.717
I'm out.

15:17.717 --> 15:18.951
[ Smacks lips ]

15:18.951 --> 15:22.088
All right, so, it's just
such a competitive space,

15:22.088 --> 15:24.991
and I don't have enough
expertise in the beauty space.

15:24.991 --> 15:26.325
I'm out.

15:26.325 --> 15:28.394
Daymond,
I'm sorry to hear that.
Greiner: I have a question.

15:28.394 --> 15:32.832
You showed those pictures
of hair growth.
Mm‐hmm. Mm‐hmm.

15:32.832 --> 15:35.101
Have you done any testing,

15:35.101 --> 15:39.972
any laboratory or trials
or clinicals or anything?

15:39.972 --> 15:41.073
So, clinical testing
is actually part

15:41.073 --> 15:42.341
of the market expanding,
part of what, you know,

15:42.341 --> 15:44.277
we're looking
for the funding for.
But you don't have that.

15:44.277 --> 15:47.046
To me, all it does
is signal a red flag,

15:47.046 --> 15:49.982
because when you put out
anything like that

15:49.982 --> 15:52.018
into the consumer market,

15:52.018 --> 15:55.054
you really have to have
a lot of proof backing that up,

15:55.054 --> 15:56.389
because you don't
have the clinicals.

15:56.389 --> 15:59.358
So I'm sorry ‐‐ I'm out.
But the customers are giving
their experience.

15:59.358 --> 16:02.128
But as a product person
and as a Shark,

16:02.128 --> 16:03.296
there's tons
of fake scam ads.

16:03.296 --> 16:05.298
Absolutely.
And we don't do that.
Absolutely.

16:05.298 --> 16:07.967
And we are all victim
to those fake scam ads

16:07.967 --> 16:10.036
because they'll photoshop
our images

16:10.036 --> 16:12.038
and they'll say
that we back that,

16:12.038 --> 16:13.272
and we don't at all.

16:13.272 --> 16:16.042
So, now I have to be
triply careful.

16:16.042 --> 16:17.109
Well, Lori's red flag

16:17.109 --> 16:19.745
might be this character's
greatest attraction.

16:19.745 --> 16:20.413
[ Laughter ]

16:20.413 --> 16:23.216
So, I look at it and say
what you do have is sales ‐‐

16:23.216 --> 16:25.284
a potential
of $2 million in sales

16:25.284 --> 16:28.287
if this works out
with this retailer.

16:28.287 --> 16:30.423
There's a lot of risk
in this thing.

16:30.423 --> 16:33.059
I don't think the business is
worth $4 million today.

16:33.059 --> 16:34.193
I'm sorry.

16:34.193 --> 16:36.128
I'll give you the $400,000.

16:36.128 --> 16:37.663
I want 37%.

16:37.663 --> 16:38.631
Ohh!

16:38.631 --> 16:44.770
♪♪

16:48.808 --> 16:50.343
Narrator: Four Sharks are out.

16:50.343 --> 16:53.079
Kevin is
Stephane and Yve's last chance

16:53.079 --> 16:55.748
to make a deal for
their skin‐care company,

16:55.748 --> 16:57.016
Kreyol Essence.

16:57.016 --> 16:59.051
I'll give you the $400,000,

16:59.051 --> 17:00.653
I want 37%.

17:00.653 --> 17:01.587
Ohh!

17:02.388 --> 17:05.858
Okay, thank you so much
for that offer.

17:05.858 --> 17:08.895
Would you do $400,000
for 20%?

17:08.895 --> 17:10.663
Never. Never.

17:10.663 --> 17:11.864
Never.

17:11.864 --> 17:13.299
This has risks.

17:13.299 --> 17:15.001
<i>All</i> businesses
have risks.

17:15.001 --> 17:16.235
Look,
I'm impressed by you.

17:16.235 --> 17:18.004
Now we're having
a tough‐love discussion.

17:18.004 --> 17:19.171
Mm‐hmm.
It's about money.

17:19.171 --> 17:21.007
I want to <i>make</i> money.

17:21.007 --> 17:23.209
37% is too rich.
No, it isn't.

17:23.209 --> 17:25.144
Can you meet me
in the middle, at 25%?

17:25.144 --> 17:27.213
No.
No, no, no.

17:27.213 --> 17:29.515
Look, you have
to make a decision.
Mm‐hmm.

17:29.515 --> 17:32.585
I'll still have the $400,000
when you walk out that door,

17:32.585 --> 17:36.188
and someone else will
be sitting in front of me.
Yes, and I will still
have that, you know, account

17:36.188 --> 17:38.224
where I'm gonna make
$2 million this year

17:38.224 --> 17:40.059
and go on
to make $5‐, $10‐,

17:40.059 --> 17:42.261
and make sure
that we get to $100 million.

17:42.261 --> 17:45.431
Because that's what businesses
of our rank and size have done,

17:45.431 --> 17:47.199
and I want you
to be part of that.
I get it.

17:47.199 --> 17:48.301
But that is too high.
But this is your moment.

17:48.301 --> 17:51.337
You have to make a decision.
But 37% is way too high.

17:51.337 --> 17:53.105
There's no way
we could give that much.
Everybody says that.

17:53.105 --> 17:56.208
You know, if you don't like it,
don't take it.

17:56.208 --> 17:58.778
Lots of risk.
That's why they call it
the Shark Tank.

17:58.778 --> 18:00.212
♪♪

18:00.212 --> 18:02.048
Jean‐Baptiste:
What are some of your ideas?

18:02.048 --> 18:03.950
What would you do
to essentially help us?

18:03.950 --> 18:05.084
Oh, now you got to
sell yourself?

18:05.084 --> 18:06.285
I don't have to sell myself.
I'm Mr. Wonderful.

18:06.285 --> 18:07.386
I'm not asking you
to sell yourself.

18:07.386 --> 18:09.188
We're having a conversation.
You know what I do?

18:09.188 --> 18:10.389
We're having a tough‐love
conversation.

18:10.389 --> 18:12.058
Tough‐love conversation,
Mr. Wonderful.

18:12.058 --> 18:13.125
All right.
I'll justify myself.

18:13.125 --> 18:15.094
I have $400,000.
You don't.

18:15.094 --> 18:17.363
[ Laughter ]

18:17.363 --> 18:20.166
Wow.
Make a decision.
Jean‐Baptiste: We recognize
that sales cures all.

18:20.166 --> 18:21.601
Yes.
You know, in 2016,
we were getting ready

18:21.601 --> 18:24.136
to shut down the business
because of having lost that ‐‐

18:24.136 --> 18:25.438
Don't tell me that.
I don't want to hear that.

18:25.438 --> 18:28.975
No, no, for sure.
You're not focusing
on the issue at hand.

18:28.975 --> 18:32.111
$400,000 for 37% ‐‐
yes or no?

18:32.111 --> 18:40.186
♪♪

18:40.186 --> 18:43.889
Stephane,
you are very emotional.

18:43.889 --> 18:45.758
Can you share why?

18:46.959 --> 18:47.560
[ Sighs ]

18:47.560 --> 18:51.063
That time period was
really tough for us, in 2016.

18:51.063 --> 18:52.331
I mean, even to the point

18:52.331 --> 18:55.167
where we almost just
closed the business down.

18:55.167 --> 18:57.036
It challenged
our relationship,

18:57.036 --> 18:59.538
you know, feeling
as if we sort of...

18:59.538 --> 19:02.375
We failed our community.
...failed our community,
failed ourselves.

19:02.375 --> 19:05.277
It's not just about
the great products.

19:05.277 --> 19:07.146
It's about the mission
of helping

19:07.146 --> 19:10.216
to create a blueprint
for poverty alleviation,

19:10.216 --> 19:13.185
which is a huge problem
around the world.

19:13.185 --> 19:16.255
It's my culture.
It's my identity. It's...

19:16.255 --> 19:17.456
[ Sniffles ]

19:17.456 --> 19:21.293
It's everything that my parents
sacrificed to get us here.

19:21.293 --> 19:23.062
I mean,
we shouldn't be here.

19:23.062 --> 19:24.497
♪♪

19:24.497 --> 19:27.900
But you <i>are</i> here,
and you have an offer.

19:27.900 --> 19:28.367
[ Laughs ]

19:28.367 --> 19:31.170
What have you
decided to do?

19:31.170 --> 19:32.571
♪♪

19:32.571 --> 19:35.408
Uh, Mr. Wonderful,
would you be interested ‐‐

19:35.408 --> 19:38.177
thinking through this ‐‐
doing a royalty deal?

19:38.177 --> 19:43.015
♪♪

19:43.015 --> 19:44.016
Royalty?

19:44.016 --> 19:45.017
Yes.

19:46.285 --> 19:48.220
That brings a tear
to <i>my</i> eye.

19:48.220 --> 19:49.488
[ Laughter ]

19:49.488 --> 19:52.158
I'd like to hear
what you have in mind.

19:53.125 --> 19:55.127
15 cents
for every bottle sold.

19:55.127 --> 19:56.462
♪♪

19:56.462 --> 19:59.265
So I don't have any equity?
It's just a royalty?

19:59.265 --> 20:01.167
It's just
a royalty deal.

20:01.167 --> 20:03.135
[ Sighs ]

20:03.135 --> 20:05.504
Tell you what ‐‐
final offer.

20:05.504 --> 20:10.342
I want 25 cents royalty
on every unit sold in perpetuity

20:10.342 --> 20:13.045
and 5% equity,
and you have a deal.

20:13.045 --> 20:17.383
♪♪

20:17.383 --> 20:19.351
You have a deal.
Let's do it.

20:19.351 --> 20:21.387
[ Greiner chuckles ]
Corcoran: Wow!
What a turnaround!

20:21.387 --> 20:22.988
I didn't see that coming.

20:22.988 --> 20:24.090
[ Laughs ]
Thank you.

20:24.090 --> 20:25.157
Congratulations.
Good luck.

20:25.157 --> 20:27.126
‐Congrats.
‐Thank you.

20:27.126 --> 20:29.261
Corcoran: Wow.
What a surprise twist.

20:29.261 --> 20:31.464
Boy, she's got a lot of fire
in that belly.

20:31.464 --> 20:33.966
We did a royalty deal.
[ Laughs ]

20:33.966 --> 20:35.501
Whoo!

20:35.501 --> 20:38.137
No, I was not expecting
Mr. Wonderful.
So, we were not expecting
Mr. Wonderful.

20:38.137 --> 20:39.205
[ Laughs ]
Yes.

20:39.205 --> 20:40.606
To be a partner
in a Haitian beauty brand?

20:40.606 --> 20:43.476
Yeah. [ Laughs ]
Not quite what
you think of every day.

20:43.476 --> 20:46.846
But, you know,
Kevin O'Leary surprises you.
Exactly.

20:46.846 --> 20:49.048
♪♪

20:49.048 --> 20:50.216
Narrator: In season 6,

20:50.216 --> 20:52.384
mother and son
Judy and Bobby Edwards

20:52.384 --> 20:54.253
made a deal with Lori Greiner

20:54.253 --> 20:56.288
for their toilet stool,
Squatty Potty.

20:56.288 --> 20:57.690
...squat
in a healthy position

20:57.690 --> 21:00.426
while still enjoying the comfort
of their Western toilet.

21:00.426 --> 21:03.729
Let's see how Squatty Potty
is doing now.

21:03.729 --> 21:06.732
We came on "Shark Tank"
to change the way America poops.

21:06.732 --> 21:09.668
And now Squatty Potty has become
a cultural phenomenon.

21:09.668 --> 21:12.638
With Lori on our team,
we were able to secure buyers

21:12.638 --> 21:14.740
at major retailers,
and it snowballed

21:14.740 --> 21:18.210
into an international,
multi‐million‐dollar company.

21:18.210 --> 21:19.378
I was 67 years old,

21:19.378 --> 21:22.648
and so me and my husband, Bill,
decided we wanted to retire.

21:22.648 --> 21:24.617
We were attracting great offers
to buy the business,

21:24.617 --> 21:28.387
but we weren't quite ready
to part with everything yet.

21:28.387 --> 21:32.091
So we decided on an 8‐figure,
multi‐million‐dollar deal

21:32.091 --> 21:32.658
for half of the business.

21:32.658 --> 21:34.426
I just wanted
to thank Lori Greiner

21:34.426 --> 21:36.395
for coming and attending
the board meeting.

21:36.395 --> 21:39.198
Greiner: This new partnership
has been an excellent move

21:39.198 --> 21:40.332
for Squatty Potty.

21:40.332 --> 21:41.400
I love this.

21:41.400 --> 21:43.169
There are
all these new products,

21:43.169 --> 21:44.503
all this new creativity.

21:44.503 --> 21:46.705
It's taken the brand
to a whole new level.

21:46.705 --> 21:50.476
We've now sold over 4.5 million
Squatty Potties.

21:50.476 --> 21:54.313
Bobby: Squatty Potty's partnered
with over 20 major retailers.

21:54.313 --> 21:56.682
We're also in 20 countries
all over the world.

21:56.682 --> 22:02.188
We've now done $175 million
in sales since "Shark Tank."

22:02.188 --> 22:05.357
Greiner: [ Laughing ]
Oh, my gosh!

22:05.357 --> 22:07.660
This is
insanely beautiful!

22:07.660 --> 22:10.563
Greiner: This is
a dream come true for Judy.

22:10.563 --> 22:11.764
She's built her dream home.

22:11.764 --> 22:14.433
When Judy came into the
Shark Tank with Squatty Potty,

22:14.433 --> 22:16.235
most of the other Sharks
laughed.

22:16.235 --> 22:17.469
They thought it was a joke.

22:17.469 --> 22:18.671
And look ‐‐ today,

22:18.671 --> 22:23.075
it's one of "Shark Tank's"
most successful stories ever.

22:23.075 --> 22:23.776
All: To the good life!

22:23.776 --> 22:27.379
I think what Mom shows is that
at any age, anything's possible.

22:27.379 --> 22:30.216
She was set to retire
at 60 years old, with no funds.

22:30.216 --> 22:31.650
Judy:
Then "Shark Tank" came along

22:31.650 --> 22:33.719
and put our business
in the spotlight.

22:33.719 --> 22:35.688
A lot of times,
we look at each other

22:35.688 --> 22:38.390
and go, "You know what?
This is the American dream."

22:38.390 --> 22:40.392
And we are
so grateful for it.

22:40.392 --> 22:44.330
♪♪

22:49.235 --> 22:51.670
♪♪

22:51.670 --> 22:56.208
Narrator: Next up is a product
that helps couples stay in sync.

22:56.208 --> 23:03.515
♪♪

23:03.515 --> 23:05.684
Hello, Sharks. I'm Jenn.
And I'm Ryan.

23:05.684 --> 23:08.621
We are the founders of LoveSync
from Cleveland, Ohio.

23:08.621 --> 23:12.258
We're seeking $100,000
for 10% of our company.

23:12.258 --> 23:13.626
Sharks, imagine this.

23:13.626 --> 23:16.362
You're out on a romantic date
with your significant other.

23:16.362 --> 23:18.264
Great food,

23:18.264 --> 23:20.466
a fine bottle
of O'Leary Merlot,

23:20.466 --> 23:22.635
[ Laughter ]
and there are
no distractions

23:22.635 --> 23:24.470
from enjoying
each other's company.

23:24.470 --> 23:26.505
I think we all know
that nights like this

23:26.505 --> 23:29.341
usually finish
with a happy end.

23:29.341 --> 23:31.477
But what about
those everyday nights

23:31.477 --> 23:35.247
when life gets in the way
and sexy times often becomes

23:35.247 --> 23:38.083
a take‐it or leave‐it
proposition?

23:38.083 --> 23:38.851
Like tonight.

23:38.851 --> 23:40.920
He could be down for
a little dance in the sheets,

23:40.920 --> 23:45.257
but he assumes that she is
exhausted from a stressful day,

23:45.257 --> 23:47.159
lets the moment pass.

23:47.159 --> 23:47.893
Little does he know,

23:47.893 --> 23:51.497
she'd be up for
a quick bed boogie to unwind,

23:51.497 --> 23:53.465
but she <i>is</i> tired,
and she figures

23:53.465 --> 23:55.734
it's gonna take more energy
than she's got tonight

23:55.734 --> 23:58.437
to distract him
away from his work.

23:58.437 --> 24:01.473
The reality is,
these types of situations

