I can get costs down, though,
to about $1.70 or $1.80.

35:15.113 --> 35:16.848
And what do you sell it for?

35:16.848 --> 35:18.149
On my website, for $12.

35:18.149 --> 35:19.284
Greiner: $12?
Yes.

35:19.284 --> 35:20.685
And people are willing
to pay $12 a jar?

35:20.685 --> 35:24.889
Yes. I've actually
never had anyone complain
about $12 per jar.

35:24.889 --> 35:25.590
Really?
Yeah.

35:25.590 --> 35:28.126
Did you do any type
of market research, though,

35:28.126 --> 35:30.362
where you would, like,
reach out to people

35:30.362 --> 35:33.231
and ask them,
"Would you buy this?

35:33.231 --> 35:35.133
How often would you use it?" ‐‐
things like that.

35:35.133 --> 35:36.601
Um...not formally.

35:36.601 --> 35:40.205
But also, I've learned people
have no idea what they do want.

35:40.205 --> 35:41.339
You know?
Amen.

35:41.339 --> 35:43.208
The challenge with that is,
you're there, right?

35:43.208 --> 35:45.076
And you're educating them,
right?

35:45.076 --> 35:46.878
When I first started,
I used to stand out

35:46.878 --> 35:48.546
on 125th Street in Harlem,

35:48.546 --> 35:51.383
right outside the Apollo
when the Apollo Theater let out,

35:51.383 --> 35:53.451
and I got
really good responses.

35:53.451 --> 35:56.388
They told me what they thought
about my T‐shirts <i>and</i> my mama.

35:56.388 --> 35:58.523
Everything.
[ Laughter ]

35:58.523 --> 36:01.026
But then, when I went
to put it in stores,

36:01.026 --> 36:02.260
it didn't move.

36:02.260 --> 36:05.230
When nobody was there
to tell the story,

36:05.230 --> 36:06.264
I got stuck.

36:06.264 --> 36:07.999
So, I think
it's a crowded market

36:07.999 --> 36:09.167
that I know nothing about,

36:09.167 --> 36:11.369
and I think it's gonna
be a challenge, really,

36:11.369 --> 36:14.039
just educating people
on how badly they need this.

36:14.039 --> 36:15.674
So I'm out.

36:16.741 --> 36:17.242
Okay.

36:17.242 --> 36:19.244
I feel like
it's very early

36:19.244 --> 36:22.147
for us to know
if people want dates or not.

36:22.147 --> 36:23.948
It was delicious.

36:23.948 --> 36:26.051
I wish you good luck...

36:26.051 --> 36:27.185
Can I ‐‐
...but I'm gonna go out.

36:27.185 --> 36:29.220
Well, I hope
you change your mind.

36:29.220 --> 36:32.223
I'm gonna make dates
mainstream

36:32.223 --> 36:35.493
the same way avocados
and cauliflower ‐‐ everything.

36:35.493 --> 36:38.697
That's why I chose flavors
to lower the inhibitions

36:38.697 --> 36:41.366
of customers who have
never had dates, heard of dates,

36:41.366 --> 36:42.567
don't know
the health benefits.

36:42.567 --> 36:45.203
But, Melissa, why didn't you do
just a plain flavor

36:45.203 --> 36:46.471
for people
who like dates?

36:46.471 --> 36:50.075
So, I do have, actually ‐‐
I just developed a plain flavor.

36:50.075 --> 36:52.143
Well, why the flavors at all
to start?

36:52.143 --> 36:54.279
If you're gonna turn dates
into a superfood,

36:54.279 --> 36:56.281
you got to let
the star of the show

36:56.281 --> 36:57.449
be the star of the show.

36:57.449 --> 36:59.117
So, where are you going
with this, Mark?

36:59.117 --> 37:00.985
I'm disappointed
in some respects.

37:00.985 --> 37:07.792
♪♪

37:11.229 --> 37:13.364
Narrator: Two Sharks are out.

37:13.364 --> 37:15.567
And Mark has an issue
with the line of flavors

37:15.567 --> 37:19.270
of Melissa's date butter
company, Wanna Date?

37:19.270 --> 37:20.538
The plain flavor's coming.

37:20.538 --> 37:23.174
I know,
but would you do <i>just</i> that?

37:23.174 --> 37:25.410
And abandon all the flavors?
For right now, yeah.

37:25.410 --> 37:27.445
Because if you want
to make it a superfood,

37:27.445 --> 37:29.347
make it
the star of the show.

37:29.347 --> 37:32.083
Here's where, for me,
it falls apart.

37:32.083 --> 37:33.785
When I was starting
my business,

37:33.785 --> 37:37.222
if I didn't make a deal
within two weeks, I was dead.

37:37.222 --> 37:39.524
I needed to live somewhere
and eat.

37:39.524 --> 37:42.227
What is in your way,
I believe,

37:42.227 --> 37:43.762
is that your father
is helping you,

37:43.762 --> 37:48.399
because succeeding is an <i>option,</i>
versus a necessity.

37:48.399 --> 37:50.435
And I found that the people
that really succeed

37:50.435 --> 37:51.569
have a real necessity.

37:51.569 --> 37:54.439
They have to do it
or the sky's gonna fall in.

37:54.439 --> 37:55.640
With the absence of that,

37:55.640 --> 37:58.076
I can't believe it enough
to put my money in,

37:58.076 --> 37:59.244
so for that reason,
I'm out.

37:59.244 --> 38:02.180
♪♪

38:02.180 --> 38:05.350
Well...I won't be homeless
if this fails,

38:05.350 --> 38:07.585
but I do everything
on my own.

38:07.585 --> 38:09.954
[ Voice breaking ]
I've ‐‐ I run my web‐‐

38:09.954 --> 38:10.588
Sorry.

38:10.588 --> 38:13.124
Like, my dad
just believes in me.

38:13.124 --> 38:15.326
You know, like, I'm...

38:15.326 --> 38:16.661
I'm...

38:16.661 --> 38:19.497
I've never had anything
handed to me in my whole life.

38:19.497 --> 38:21.466
I'm not, like, a rich kid.

38:21.466 --> 38:22.600
I don't sleep.

38:22.600 --> 38:26.037
I carry cases of this
all over New York.

38:26.037 --> 38:27.205
I work events.

38:27.205 --> 38:29.541
I do them all myself.
Nobody helps me.

38:29.541 --> 38:31.442
But take away
that security blanket

38:31.442 --> 38:32.710
of having your rent paid,

38:32.710 --> 38:36.047
and the comparison would be,
like, night and day

38:36.047 --> 38:37.282
what you can accomplish.

38:37.282 --> 38:39.517
I've seen it over and over again
with so many people.

38:39.517 --> 38:41.219
Failure's just when you quit.

38:41.219 --> 38:43.221
I don't quit,
so this won't fail,

38:43.221 --> 38:45.490
'cause I will go
until it succeeds.

38:45.490 --> 38:46.658
John:
Listen, I started out,

38:46.658 --> 38:49.460
and my mother
mortgaged the house.

38:49.460 --> 38:51.429
And without her
mortgaging the home,

38:51.429 --> 38:53.598
I couldn't have financed
my first couple of shirts.

38:53.598 --> 38:55.466
So, I mean,
that's Barbara's opinion.

38:55.466 --> 38:56.601
You know what, Melissa,
I don't agree.

38:56.601 --> 38:58.603
I understand
from an investment perspective.

38:58.603 --> 39:01.372
There <i>is</i> value when someone's
back is against the wall.

39:01.372 --> 39:03.274
We've all faced it, right?

39:03.274 --> 39:04.676
But that's like saying,
if Barbara's right,

39:04.676 --> 39:07.345
that means none of our kids can
ever do anything on their own,

39:07.345 --> 39:09.247
and I can't ‐‐
I refuse to believe that.

39:09.247 --> 39:10.615
Like, I hate
asking him for money,

39:10.615 --> 39:12.717
and this is the first time
I've ever had to.

39:12.717 --> 39:15.353
[ Sniffles ] And I'm gonna
pay him every single penny back.

39:15.353 --> 39:17.088
That's why I work hard
every day.

39:18.356 --> 39:20.758
Melissa, my problem
with your deal is...

39:20.758 --> 39:24.462
it's too early to be worth
half a million bucks.

39:24.462 --> 39:26.497
There's a lot
that's going to happen

39:26.497 --> 39:28.433
before you actually get scale.

39:28.433 --> 39:31.069
And I wish you the best,
but I'm out.

39:31.069 --> 39:34.272
♪♪

39:34.272 --> 39:36.107
So, now
there's me and you.

39:38.109 --> 39:39.277
Do you have competition?

39:39.277 --> 39:42.247
Is there anybody else
selling date butter?

39:42.247 --> 39:43.581
The closest thing is one

39:43.581 --> 39:46.417
that's full of coconut oil,
coconut butter.

39:46.417 --> 39:48.453
It's 10 times the calories.

39:48.453 --> 39:50.521
It has fat,
it has cholesterol.

39:50.521 --> 39:52.557
I just went vegetarian,
so I'm always looking

39:52.557 --> 39:55.460
for things that are healthy,
healthy for my family.

39:55.460 --> 39:56.761
Absolutely.
When you walked in,

39:56.761 --> 39:59.664
and other than thinking "What
the hell is this?" initially,

39:59.664 --> 40:02.533
the idea of a date spread
was great,

40:02.533 --> 40:03.835
'cause I love dates.

40:03.835 --> 40:07.372
But you got to be smaller,
cheaper, easier to ship,

40:07.372 --> 40:09.540
and you have to make dates
just plain.

40:09.540 --> 40:10.775
Are you willing
to do all that?

40:10.775 --> 40:13.678
Absolutely. We can look into
other packaging options.

40:13.678 --> 40:16.147
Absolutely.
Okay.
So I'll make you an offer.

40:16.147 --> 40:18.416
♪♪

40:18.416 --> 40:21.519
$100,000,
but I want 33%.

40:21.519 --> 40:22.520
33%?
Right.

40:22.520 --> 40:24.289
Because it's gonna
take some time,

40:24.289 --> 40:25.423
it's gonna take
some effort.

40:25.423 --> 40:26.691
But there you go.
That's your offer.

40:26.691 --> 40:28.359
You got an offer.
What do you want to do?

40:29.794 --> 40:32.330
Because I've learned
that it never hurts to ask ‐‐

40:32.330 --> 40:33.798
No.
No?

40:33.798 --> 40:35.633
Greiner: Oh, my God.
Well, he answered already.

40:35.633 --> 40:37.568
You can counter.
Do it.

40:37.568 --> 40:39.637
Go with your gut.
This is your business.

40:39.637 --> 40:42.040
Just tell Mark Cuban
to take a walk.

40:42.040 --> 40:46.644
♪♪

40:46.644 --> 40:48.513
I'll take it.
I want to work with you.

40:48.513 --> 40:51.182
[ Laughter ]
I'll take 33% for $100,000.

40:51.182 --> 40:51.783
Ta‐da!

40:51.783 --> 40:54.385
Thank you, Mark!
O'Leary: Smart move, Melissa.

40:54.385 --> 40:55.687
Smart move.
Greiner: Congratulations.

40:55.687 --> 40:57.388
I appreciate it.
I'm excited.

40:57.388 --> 40:58.523
I'm excited.
O'Leary: Smart move.

40:58.523 --> 41:00.325
Thank you, everyone.
Greiner: Congratulations.

41:00.325 --> 41:02.427
‐Good luck.
‐We'll talk soon.

41:02.427 --> 41:05.363
♪♪

41:05.363 --> 41:06.531
Oh, my God.

41:06.531 --> 41:08.666
I've been an underdog
my whole life.

41:08.666 --> 41:09.734
Barbara not believing in me

41:09.734 --> 41:11.569
is just one
in another million people,

41:11.569 --> 41:13.338
and I always prove
everyone wrong.

41:13.338 --> 41:14.572
I just work harder.

41:14.572 --> 41:17.475
I put my head down and hustle,
and I'll just keep doing that.

41:17.475 --> 41:18.776
It's what I've always done
and always will do.

41:18.776 --> 41:20.478
Did you notice,
after I insulted her,

41:20.478 --> 41:21.612
she was
a different person?

41:21.612 --> 41:22.780
I like the way
you beat her up.
Greiner: Yeah.

41:22.780 --> 41:25.783
That's what I wanted to see,
if she had what it took.

41:25.783 --> 41:28.619
I think Mark brought up a point.
Why did you insult her?

41:28.619 --> 41:30.688
Because none of our kids
will be successful because ‐‐

41:30.688 --> 41:33.424
No. You know why? Because
there are a lot of wealthy kids

41:33.424 --> 41:34.692
that become
extremely successful,

41:34.692 --> 41:35.960
and I expect it
of my children.

41:35.960 --> 41:38.563
But until I insulted her,
I wasn't feeling her vibe.

41:38.563 --> 41:40.598
Boy, she fought back,
and that was the difference.

41:40.598 --> 41:42.367
She came back like a fighter.
That's what I want to see.

